{{material-stub}}

In [[Flight dynamics (fixed-wing aircraft)|aircraft flight dynamics]], '''post stall''' is a flight condition in which the aircraft velocity has become lower than [[Stall (fluid mechanics)|stall]] speed, in order to overcome stalling in the aircraft. In this state —below the low-velocity limit of the [[flight domain]]— the wings no longer provide enough [[Lift (force)|lift]] to compensate the aircraft weight. Some aircraft, such as [[Fighter aircraft|fighter jets]], have enough engine [[thrust]] to maintain flight at those speeds. Normal [[Flight control surfaces|flight controls]], such as [[Aileron|ailerons]] and [[Elevator (aeronautics)|elevators]], may then no longer be sufficient to maintain full control of the aircraft.
